SIMPLE: hurtle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hurtle
<hw>Hur"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Hurtled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hurtling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hurtlen</ets>, freq. of <ets>hurten</ets>. See <er>Hurt</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>, and cf. <er>Hurl</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To meet
with violence or shock; to clash; to jostle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Together <qex>hurtled</qex> both their steeds.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move rapidly; to wheel or rush suddenly or with
violence; to whirl round rapidly; to skirmish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>hurtling</qex> round, advantage for to take.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Down the <qex>hurtling</qex> cataract of the ages.</q> <rj><qau>R.
L. Stevenson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make a threatening sound, like the clash of arms;
to make a sound as of confused clashing or confusion; to
resound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The noise of battle <qex>hurtled</qex> in the air.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The earthquake sound⟦br⟧
<qex>Hurtling</qex> 'death the solid ground.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hurtle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hurtle
<hw>Hur"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move
with violence or impetuosity; to whirl; to brandish.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His harmful club he gan to <qex>hurtle</qex> high.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To push; to jostle; to hurl.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And he <qex>hurtleth</qex> with his horse adown.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hurtleberry</ent>⟦br⟧
